OPHIC%20ERUPTION%20IN%20THE%2079%20C.E.htm | title=Avalanche-associated mass flows damaged Pompeii several times before the Vesuvius catastrophic eruption in the 79 CE | publisher=2004 Denver Annual Meeting | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last=Stefani | first=Grete | date=October 2006 | title=La vera data dell'eruzione | publisher=Archeo | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Steven | first=Ellis | year=2004 | title=The distribution of bars at Pompeii: Archaeological, spatial and viewshed analyses | journal=Journal of Roman Archaeology | volume=17 | issue=1 | issn=1047-7594 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last=Zarmati | first=Louise | authorlink=Louise Zarmati | year=2005 | title=Heinemann ancient and medieval history: Pompeii and Herculaneum | publisher=Heinemann | isbn=1-74081-195-X | ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=Pompeii}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Pompeii\n  |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{curlie|Regional/Europe/Italy/Regions/Campania/Localities/Pompei}}\n* [http://www.fastionline.org/ Data on new excavations] from the International Association for Classical Archaeology (AIAC)\n* [http://www.ancient.eu/pompeii/ Ancient History Encyclopedia \u2013 Pompeii]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081004031835/http://archive.cyark.org/pompeii-intro Forum of Pompeii Digital Media Archive] ([[creative commons]]-licensed photos, laser scans, panoramas), data from a [[University of Ferrara]]/[[CyArk]] research partnership\n* {{cite web |url=http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/433032 |title=Places: 433032 (Pompeii) |author1=N. Purcell |author2=R. Talbert |author3=T. Elliott |author4=S. Gillies |accessdate=March 8, 2012 | publisher=Pleiades}}\n* [http://www.alldocumentaries.org/pompeii-mystery-people-frozen-time/ Pompeii: The Mystery Of People Frozen In Time]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps/ms?msid=203702705023246089166.0004c8c8a04529ec7ba4a&msa=0 Annotated Google map and satellite view]\n\n{{Archaeological sites in Campania}}\n{{Archaeological site of Pompeii}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in Italy}}\n{{Landmarks of Campania}}\n{{Ancient Rome topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pompeii (ancient city)| ]]\n<!--present day-->\n[[Category:Archaeological museums in Italy]]\n[[Category:Archaeological parks]]\n[[Category:Mount Vesuvius]]\n[[Category:Museums in Campania]]\n[[Category:Museums of ancient Rome in Italy]]\n[[Category:National museums of Italy]]\n[[Category:Roman sites of Campania]]\n[[Category:Ruins in Italy]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Campania]]\n<!--history-->\n[[Category:1748 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:70s disestablishments in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Destroyed cities]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Italy]]\n[[Category:Human remains (archaeological)]]\n[[Category:Italic archaeological sites]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan City of Naples]]\n[[Category:Osci]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 79]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in the 1st century]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 6th century BC]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 7th century BC]]\n[[Category:Roman Empire paintings]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Italy]]\n[[Category:Natural disaster ghost towns]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Campania]]\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRediscovery and excavations:hyphen to en dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pompeii"}
{"title_page": "Pere Marquette Lumber Company", "text_new": "[[File:Pere Marquette Lumber Company store.jpg|thumb|upright 1.4|right|Pere Marquette Lumber Company store|<center><big>Pere Marquette Lumber Company</big></center>]]\nThe '''Pere Marquette Lumber Company''' was a lumber, salt, [[Sawyer (occupation)|sawyering]] and merchandising company of the nineteenth century. Its holdings were the cradle for the development of the city of [[Ludington, Michigan]]. It was an important component of the lumber [[Boomtown|boom]] and bust in the area, supplying lumber for hundreds of thousands of homes and other structures in the [[Midwest]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:The Big Store (Ludington).jpg|thumb|upright 1.250|right|<center>Advertisement in city directory - 1883]]\n\nThe lumber baron and founder of Ludington, [[James Ludington]], owned 360 acres that included the lots of the village of Pere Marquette in [[Mason County, Michigan|Mason County]] in the northwestern part of [[Lower Peninsula of Michigan|Michigan in its lower peninsula]].{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}} The village lots were sold out to individuals and that became the core of a town that in 1873 would become the city of Ludington.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=103}} He also owned the village's sawmill.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}} It was the oldest sawmill in northwestern Michigan and had been operating since 1848.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=25}} The sawmill had been owned by different men until 1859 when it became the property of Ludington through a foreclosure.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}}\n\n== Structuring ==\nLudington owned a parcel of land of some 25,000 acres that contained [[white pine]] timber. It was situated on the [[Pere Marquette River]] in [[Mason County, Michigan|Mason County]], [[Lake County, Michigan|Lake County]], [[Newaygo County]], and [[Oceana County]] in northwestern [[Michigan]] near the village of Pere Marquette.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=103}}\n\nLudington had failing health in the late 1860s and felt he could no longer manage his vast holdings in Michigan. The Pere Marquette Lumber Company was then formed to buy his holdings to take over the management. The new lumber company arrangement came under the guidance of [[Delos L. Filer]].{{sfn|Record|1895|page=117}} Ludington's holdings were bought out by the new lumber company with [[U.S. Dollars|$]]500,000 cash. It was officially organized on July 24, 1869. The members of the new company were Ludington, [[Delos L. Filer]], [[John Mason Loomis]], [[Edward A. Foster]] and [[Luther H. Foster]]. The officers of the new company were Delos L. Filer as president, John Mason Loomis as treasurer, and L. H. Foster with James Ludington as secretaries. The stock of the new lumber company was divided up proportionally when they pooled together the money to buy out Ludington's holdings.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}}{{sfn|Page|1882|page=45}}{{sfn|Hanna|1955|page=20}}\n\nLudington had built a large commercial store in the village of Pere Marquette built in 1867 called The Big Store. The store sold all kinds of general merchandise to the public. For years it was the largest retailer for Mason County. It advertised with the slogan \"Large sales and small profits.\"  The second story of the building was used for the offices of the lumber company and from time to time as a church and public library.{{sfn|Cabot|2005|page=103}}\n\nThe sawmills of the Pere Marquette Lumber Company consisted originally of the basic saws of the time when first operated in the 1870s. They manufactured about three to four million [[board feet]] (FBM) of lumber yearly. The company gradually improved and updated the machinery of their sawmills as time went on to the latest equipment. They were capable of producing 10,000,000 board feet per year by 1880. Later more improvements were added to their sawmills so that 12 to 15 million FBM per year could be produced.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=250}}\n\nThe company branched out into the [[salt]] business in 1883. At that time they started boring a well for a salt bed. They were successful in 1885 when they had drilled a well 2,220 feet deep. The company used left over lumber from their sawmills in its production for burning to distill salt from the brine they brought up from their well. The company had the capability to produce about four hundred barrels of salt per day when they first started producing salt in 1885.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=p5kcAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+Lumber+Company%22+%22Delos+L.+Filer.%22&q=%22ranks+among+the+largest+salt+%22#v=onepage&q&f 104]}} They annually produced about 90,000 [[Barrel (unit)|barrel]]s of salt by 1898.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}} The grades of salt they produced were No. 1 fine grade, and packers' salt. The Pere Marquette Lumber Company in the city of Ludington ranked among the largest salt and lumber producers in the state of Michigan by 1890. These were important industries as they helped develop the city.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}}\n\nThe company ceased operating in 1897 when its timber supply was used up.{{sfn| Nagle|2015|pages=41-42}} The Pere Marquette Lumber Company was sold to Michigan Salt Association in 1900.{{sfn|Nagle|2015|page=215}}\n\nThe Company should not be confused with the Pere Marquette Lumber and Boom Company.{{efn-ua|3 and 1/4 billion board feet of lumber were transported out of the Ludington area from 1870 to 1896.  This is enough lumber to build 312,000 three bedroom homes.  Much of it went into Chicago following the [[Great Chicago Fire]]. Each year, the Pere Marquette Lumber and Boom Company was supplying 200 million board feet of [[Log driving|logs driven]] down the river for milling in Ludington.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hUo3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA62 |title=Manistee National Forest (N.F.), Pere Marquette Wild and Scenic River (WSR), Proposed, Environmental Impact Statement |date=December 31, 1976 |accessdate=September 29, 2019 |publisher=[[Manistee National Forest]] |page=62}}</ref>}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThree cubic feet in 17 binders of the company's records are in the [[Michigan State University|Michigan State University Archives and Historical Collections]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.msu.edu/findaid/031.html |title=Pere Marquette Lumber Company Records 00031|publisher= Michigan State University Archives and Historical Collections |accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book |quote=The Pere Marquette Lumber Company ranks among the largest salt and lumber producers of the State. |URL=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5kcAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+Lumber+Company%22+%22Delos+L.+Filer.%22&q=%22ranks+among+the+largest+salt+%22#v=onepage&q&f |title= Cyclopedia of Michigan |first1=John |last1= Bersey |isbn= |type= |publisher=Western Publishing & Engraving Company|date=1890 |series= |location=New York City|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxC4hZNgay8C&pg=PA3&dq=%22Pere+Marquette%22+%22Big+Store%22+Ludington&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Ludington 1830-1930 |first1=James L. |last1= Cabot|type= |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |date=2005 |series=Images of America |location=San Francisco, California |isbn=0-7385-3951-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL= |title= Sand, Sawdust and Saw Logs; Lumber Days in Ludington |first1=Frances C. |last1= Hanna |isbn= |type= |publisher=Edwards Brothers, Inc. |date=1955 |series= |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book| quote= In 1883 this company engaged in the manufacture of salt and now make about 90,000 barrels a year.  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5c4AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Hotchkiss,+George+Woodward+(1898).+%22History+of+the+Lumber+and+Forest+Industry+of+the+Northwest%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiOmpid8OHkAhVKAqwKHZZvDmIQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=Hotchkiss%2C%20George%20Woodward%20(1898).%20%22History%20of%20the%20Lumber%20and%20Forest%20Industry%20of%20the%20Northwest%22&f=false |title=History of the Forest Industry of Northwest |first1=George Woodward |last1=Hotchkiss |isbn= |type= |publisher=G.W. Hotchkiss & Company |date=1898 |series= |location=Chicago, Illinois |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL=|title= Justus S. Stearns: Michigan Pine King and Kentucky Coal Baron, 1845-1933 |first1=Michael W. |last1= Nagle|isbn= 0814341276 |type= |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |date= 2015 |series= |location=Detroit, Michigan|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL=https://books.google.com/books?id=17E-AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover |title= History of Mason County, MI |first1=H.R. |last1=Page |isbn= |type= |publisher=H.R. Page |date=1882 |series= |location=Chicago, Illinois |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL= |title= The story of Ludington: Born of Logs, Nurtured by Car Ferries. Forged by Resilience |first1=Paul S. |last1=Peterson |type= |publisher=Heritage Publishing |date=2011 |series= |isbn=978-1-935438-08-3|location=Phoenix, Arizona |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/portraitandbiog01pubgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/portraitandbiog01pubgoog/page/n65 3] |quote=1895 Portrait and biographical record of northern Michigan Chicago, Illinois: Record Publishing Company. |title= Record of Northern Michigan |first1= |last1=Record |isbn= |type= |publisher=Record Publishing Company |date=1895 |series= |location=Chicago, Illinois |ref=harv}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pere Marquette Lumber Company}}\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1897]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Defunct manufacturing companies]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pere Marquette Lumber Company store.jpg|thumb|upright 1.4|right|Pere Marquette Lumber Company store|<center><big>Pere Marquette Lumber Company</big></center>]]\nThe '''Pere Marquette Lumber Company''' was a lumber, salt, [[Sawyer (occupation)|sawyering]] and merchandising company of the nineteenth century. Its holdings were the cradle for the development of the city of [[Ludington, Michigan]]. It was an important component of the lumber [[Boomtown|boom]] and bust in the area, supplying lumber for hundreds of thousands of homes and other structures in the [[Midwest]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:The Big Store (Ludington).jpg|thumb|upright 1.250|right|<center>Advertisement in city directory - 1883]]\n\nThe lumber baron and founder of Ludington, [[James Ludington]], owned 360 acres that included the lots of the village of Pere Marquette in [[Mason County, Michigan|Mason County]] in the northwestern part of [[Lower Peninsula of Michigan|Michigan in its lower peninsula]].{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}} The village lots were sold out to individuals and that became the core of a town that in 1873 would become the city of Ludington.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=103}} He also owned the village's sawmill.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}} It was the oldest sawmill in northwestern Michigan and had been operating since 1848.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=25}} The sawmill had been owned by different men until 1859 when it became the property of Ludington through a foreclosure.{{sfn|Peterson|2011|page=26}}\n\n== Restructuring ==\nLudington owned a parcel of land of some 25,000 acres that contained [[white pine]] timber. It was situated on the [[Pere Marquette River]] in [[Mason County, Michigan|Mason County]], [[Lake County, Michigan|Lake County]], [[Newaygo County]], and [[Oceana County]] in northwestern [[Michigan]] near the village of Pere Marquette.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=103}}\n\nLudington had failing health in the late 1860s and felt he could no longer manage his vast holdings in Michigan. The Pere Marquette Lumber Company was then formed to buy his holdings to take over the management. The new lumber company arrangement came under the guidance of [[Delos L. Filer]].{{sfn|Record|1895|page=117}} Ludington's holdings were bought out by the new lumber company with [[U.S. Dollars|$]]500,000 cash. It was officially organized on July 24, 1869. The members of the new company were Ludington, [[Delos L. Filer]], [[John Mason Loomis]], [[Edward A. Foster]] and [[Luther H. Foster]]. The officers of the new company were Delos L. Filer as president, John Mason Loomis as treasurer, and L. H. Foster with James Ludington as secretaries. The stock of the new lumber company was divided up proportionally when they pooled together the money to buy out Ludington's holdings.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}}{{sfn|Page|1882|page=45}}{{sfn|Hanna|1955|page=20}}\n\nLudington had built a large commercial store in the village of Pere Marquette built in 1867 called The Big Store. The store sold all kinds of general merchandise to the public. For years it was the largest retailer for Mason County. It advertised with the slogan \"Large sales and small profits.\"  The second story of the building was used for the offices of the lumber company and from time to time as a church and public library.{{sfn|Cabot|2005|page=103}}\n\nThe sawmills of the Pere Marquette Lumber Company consisted originally of the basic saws of the time when first operated in the 1870s. They manufactured about three to four million [[board feet]] (FBM) of lumber yearly. The company gradually improved and updated the machinery of their sawmills as time went on to the latest equipment. They were capable of producing 10,000,000 board feet per year by 1880. Later more improvements were added to their sawmills so that 12 to 15 million FBM per year could be produced.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=250}}\n\nThe company branched out into the [[salt]] business in 1883. At that time they started boring a well for a salt bed. They were successful in 1885 when they had drilled a well 2,220 feet deep. The company used left over lumber from their sawmills in its production for burning to distill salt from the brine they brought up from their well. The company had the capability to produce about four hundred barrels of salt per day when they first started producing salt in 1885.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=p5kcAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+Lumber+Company%22+%22Delos+L.+Filer.%22&q=%22ranks+among+the+largest+salt+%22#v=onepage&q&f 104]}} They annually produced about 90,000 [[Barrel (unit)|barrel]]s of salt by 1898.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}} The grades of salt they produced were No. 1 fine grade, and packers' salt. The Pere Marquette Lumber Company in the city of Ludington ranked among the largest salt and lumber producers in the state of Michigan by 1890. These were important industries as they helped develop the city.{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1898|page=249}}\n\nThe company ceased operating in 1897 when its timber supply was used up.{{sfn| Nagle|2015|pages=41-42}} The Pere Marquette Lumber Company was sold to Michigan Salt Association in 1900.{{sfn|Nagle|2015|page=215}}\n\nThe Company should not be confused with the Pere Marquette Lumber and Boom Company.{{efn-ua|3 and 1/4 billion board feet of lumber were transported out of the Ludington area from 1870 to 1896.  This is enough lumber to build 312,000 three bedroom homes.  Much of it went into Chicago following the [[Great Chicago Fire]]. Each year, the Pere Marquette Lumber and Boom Company was supplying 200 million board feet of [[Log driving|logs driven]] down the river for milling in Ludington.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hUo3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA62 |title=Manistee National Forest (N.F.), Pere Marquette Wild and Scenic River (WSR), Proposed, Environmental Impact Statement |date=December 31, 1976 |accessdate=September 29, 2019 |publisher=[[Manistee National Forest]] |page=62}}</ref>}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThree cubic feet in 17 binders of the company's records are in the [[Michigan State University|Michigan State University Archives and Historical Collections]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.msu.edu/findaid/031.html |title=Pere Marquette Lumber Company Records 00031|publisher= Michigan State University Archives and Historical Collections |accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book |quote=The Pere Marquette Lumber Company ranks among the largest salt and lumber producers of the State. |URL=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5kcAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Pere+Marquette+Lumber+Company%22+%22Delos+L.+Filer.%22&q=%22ranks+among+the+largest+salt+%22#v=onepage&q&f |title= Cyclopedia of Michigan |first1=John |last1= Bersey |isbn= |type= |publisher=Western Publishing & Engraving Company|date=1890 |series= |location=New York City|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxC4hZNgay8C&pg=PA3&dq=%22Pere+Marquette%22+%22Big+Store%22+Ludington&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Ludington 1830-1930 |first1=James L. |last1= Cabot|type= |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |date=2005 |series=Images of America |location=San Francisco, California |isbn=0-7385-3951-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |URL= |title= Sand, Sawdust and Saw Logs; Lumber Days in Ludington |first1=Frances C. |last1= Hanna |isbn= |type= |publisher=Edwards Brothers, Inc. |date=1955 |series= |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book| quote= In 1883 this company engaged in the manufacture of salt and now make about 90,000 barrels a year.  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5c4AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Hotchkiss,+George+Woodward+(1898).+%22History+of+the+Lumber+and+Forest+Industry+of+the+Northwest%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiOmpid8OHkAhVKAqwKHZZvDmIQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=Hotchkiss%2C%20George%20Woodward%20(1898).%20%22History%20of%20the%20Lumber%20and%20Forest%20Industry%20of%20the%20Northwest%22&f=false |title=History of the Forest Industry of Northwest |first1=George Woodw